Overlapping happiness: An analysis of the HappyDB dataset¶

Overview and Background¶

This is a report based off the data in the HappyDB dataset: https://github.com/megagonlabs/HappyDB

The HappyDB dataset is a collection of crowd sourced happy moments. On Amazon Mechanical Turk, participants were asked to recall three happy moments.

From this information, we can glean some insight into the perception of happiness. Happiness itself is nebulous and hard to quantify -- doubly so considering the rather open ended nature of the question posed to the participants. However, there are clearly several different types of happiness. In this review, we would like to see:

1) What types of happiness is most common? 2) What is most representative for each category of happiness? 3) Are there significant overlaps between catetgories of happiness? Which types of happiness are most similar?

Question 1) What are the categories of happiness and which one is most common?¶

Luckily, this is the easiest question to answer since the HappyDB database has already provided the categories for us. We can just count the frequencies.

This mainly serves as an introductory question to the future analyses we are going to look at.

In [9]:
df.groupby("predicted_category").size()

There are seven categories of happiness: 1) achievement, 2) affection, 3) bonding, 4) enjoy_the_moment, 5) exercise, 6) leisure 7) nature.

We can see that achievement, affection, and bonding are the three most common types of happiness in descending order.

Question 2) What makes up each type of happiness?¶

Is there a common theme between different types of happiness? Using our cleaned data without stopwords, we can look at if there are common words between the different categories.

This can later tell us which types of happiness may be most similar to each other!

Metric: Words in categories of happiness¶

For each category of happiness, we are going to create a "bag of words". This contains the non-stopwords that are used in this category.

Having created this dataframe, we can look at the word frequencies and proportions to see which words are most associated with which category of happiness. This can be visually demonstrated with a word cloud.

Additionally, we can see which categories of happiness are most similar to which other categories of happiness by looking at how similar their "bag of words" or word clouds are. (Another way to think about this is having a vector where each dimension is a unique non-stopword and finding the cosine-similarity between each happiness category's vector).

In [10]:
# create a dataframe that has a word cloud for each happiness category

happiness_categories = ["achievement", "affection", "bonding", "enjoy_the_moment", "exercise", "leisure", "nature"]

word_cloud = {}

for index, row in df.iterrows():
    category = row["predicted_category"]
    
    if category not in word_cloud: #add category to dictionary
        word_cloud[category] = []
    
    word_cloud[category].extend(row["cleaned_hm_filtered"])

Question 3) Associations between categories of happiness? Which types of happiness are most similar?¶

Vector similarities (TF-IDF using NLTK)¶

Although the wordclouds gave us a good visual representation of the non-stopword frequencies per categories, it does not give us great insight into the similarities or overlap between categories.

We can do this by finding the TF-IDF vectors for each happiness category and finding the cosine similarities between them (this can be visually represented with a heatmap).

Unfortunately, because the vectors are so large, the cosine-similarity takes a long time to calculate and kills the kernel each time. Because of this, we alter the method by capping max features for the vector to 50 (this being the 50 most frequently used words throughout all the corpus).

In [19]:
#find 50 most frequently used words

word_list = []
for key in word_cloud:
    word_list.extend(word_cloud[key])

def most_common_words(words, n=50):
    word_counter = Counter(words)
    return [word for word, _ in word_counter.most_common(n)]

# most common 50
feature_words = most_common_words(word_list)

Conclusions¶

From the above vector similarities (and heatmap), we can see that the most closely similar types of happiness are "exercise" and "nature" with a score of 0.83, "leisure" and "exercise" with a score of 0.84 and "affection" and "enjoy_the_moment" with 0.84.

Least similar with a score of 0.47 is "achievement" and "bonding". This checks out considering how many people complain their career takes them away from their family (and family, going back to our word cloud from the previous section), is the most associated with bonding.
